<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does commercial exhaust hood repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our commercial diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most exhaust hood repairs run between $180 and $650. Exhaust fan motor replacement, belt replacement, bearing repair, speed control, or baffle filter cleaning/replacement is toward the mid-range. Full blower assembly replacement or ductwork repair runs higher. We provide a written estimate before any work begins. Note: NFPA 96 hood cleaning (grease duct cleaning) is a separate service from mechanical repair — cleaning services run $300–$800 depending on hood size and duct length."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between a Type I and Type II commercial exhaust hood?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Type I hoods are required over cooking equipment that produces grease-laden vapors — fryers, griddles, open burners, charbroilers, woks. They must include grease filters or baffle filters, a grease collection system, and in California, a fire suppression system. NFPA 96 governs Type I installations and requires semi-annual inspection and cleaning by a certified service. Type II hoods are used over equipment producing heat, steam, and odors without significant grease — steamers, dishwashers, ovens without open flame. They require less stringent construction and do not mandate fire suppression. The repair approach differs significantly between the two."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My restaurant exhaust hood is not pulling air — what should I check first?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Check the baffle or grease filters first. Severely grease-loaded filters reduce airflow dramatically — in a busy kitchen, filters can accumulate enough grease in 2–4 weeks to significantly reduce ventilation effectiveness. Remove and inspect the filters. If they're heavily coated with grease, cleaning or replacing them may restore airflow without any mechanical repair needed. If filters are clean and airflow is still weak, the issue is in the fan motor, belt, or ductwork — call us at (323) 870-4790."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a broken commercial exhaust hood a fire code violation in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A non-functioning exhaust hood over cooking equipment that produces grease-laden vapors (Type I application) is a fire code violation under NFPA 96 and LAFD regulations. Cooking over open flame or a fryer without functioning exhaust ventilation allows grease vapor to accumulate in the kitchen and ductwork — a serious fire risk. LAFD and LADBS health inspectors can cite this as a violation and require correction before the kitchen can operate. We treat exhaust hood failures over active cooking equipment as emergency priority calls."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Captive-Aire, Gaylord, and Halton commercial exhaust hoods?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Captive-Aire, Gaylord, and Halton are the three most common commercial exhaust hood brands in LA restaurant kitchens. We also service Accurex and custom-fabricated stainless steel hoods common in older LA restaurant installations. For residential and semi-commercial range hoods (Broan, Vent-A-Hood, Viking, Wolf range hoods), we service those as well — see our residential range hood repair service."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often does a commercial exhaust hood need service?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "NFPA 96 requires Type I hood cleaning at intervals based on cooking volume: monthly for high-volume solid fuel or charbroiler operations, quarterly for most full-service restaurants, semi-annually for lower-volume operations. Mechanical service (fan motor inspection, bearing lubrication, belt check, speed control test) should be performed annually or when problems are detected. In LA's restaurant density, many operators schedule cleaning and mechanical service on the same visit."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

